---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import MeshDiagram from "../components/MeshDiagram.astro";
---

<Base
  title="Pinet — multi-agent coordination for pi"
  description="Pinet connects pi coding agents to Slack and to each other. One broker, deterministic routing, agents that survive restarts."
  docId="PINET/OVERVIEW"
  active="home"
>
  <section class="hero">
    <div class="hero-copy">
      <h1>One gateway.<br />One message primitive.<br />Many agents.</h1>
      <p class="dek">
        Pinet is a local-first coordination layer for <a
          href="https://github.com/badlogic/pi-mono">pi</a> coding agents. A single broker watches
        Slack, routes every message, and keeps a mesh of named worker agents shipping: writing
        code, reviewing each other's pull requests, and repairing themselves when something stalls.
      </p>
      <span class="cmd"><span class="prompt">$ </span>pi install npm:@pinet/slack-bridge</span>
      <p class="small-note">requires pi · node ≥ 22 · a slack workspace where you can install apps</p>
      <div>
        <a class="xref" href="/slack-bridge/"><span class="arrow">→</span> setup in ten minutes</a>
        <a class="xref" href="/core/"><span class="arrow">→</span> how the mesh works</a>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="hero-figure">
      <MeshDiagram />
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-no">§ 01<small>subject</small></div>
    <div class="prose">
      <h2>What Pinet is</h2>
      <p>
        You mention an agent in Slack. The right agent picks the message up. If that agent dies,
        another takes over. You never think about routing, lifecycle, or thread ownership — that is
        the whole point.
      </p>
      <p>
        Underneath, Pinet runs a <strong>broker–worker model</strong>. One pi session acts as the
        broker: it owns Slack ingress, assigns work, and tracks what every worker holds. Worker
        sessions pick up tasks, write code, run tests, and open pull requests. The broker
        coordinates but does not write code; workers ship end to end.
      </p>
      <p>
        Everything rides on a single primitive, <code>message.send</code>. Slack replies,
        agent-to-agent messages, and scheduled wake-ups are the same thing underneath; adapters
        translate at the edges. The broker reasons; the routing under it is deterministic policy
        code.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-no">§ 02<small>wire path</small></div>
    <div class="prose">
      <h2>The life of a message</h2>
      <ol class="clauses">
        <li>
          <div>
            <span class="clause-title">Arrival.</span>
            <p>
              A Slack message lands over Socket Mode: a DM, an <code>@pinet</code> mention, or a
              <code>/pinet</code> slash command.
            </p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>
          <div>
            <span class="clause-title">Gatekeeping.</span>
            <p>
              Access is default-deny. The sender must be in <code>allowedUsers</code> (or the
              workspace-wide allowance must be explicit). Ingress guards can additionally require a
              mention in configured channels.
            </p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>
          <div>
            <span class="clause-title">Routing.</span>
            <p>
              The broker resolves thread ownership. A thread claimed by an agent keeps flowing to
              that agent; unclaimed work is assigned. No split brain; one control plane owns
              delivery.
            </p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>
          <div>
            <span class="clause-title">Inbox.</span>
            <p>
              The message is queued in the owner's durable inbox. Busy agents drain it on their next
              turn; restarts do not lose it.
            </p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>
          <div>
            <span class="clause-title">Work &amp; reply.</span>
            <p>
              The agent acknowledges, does the work (code, tests, PRs), and replies in the same
              thread via <code>slack_send</code>. The ball never silently drops.
            </p>
          </div>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-no">§ 03<small>doctrine</small></div>
    <div class="prose">
      <h2>Operating principles</h2>
      <dl class="defs">
        <div>
          <dt>one control plane</dt>
          <dd>A single broker owns routing, agent lifecycle, and message delivery.</dd>
        </div>
        <div>
          <dt>stable identity</dt>
          <dd>
            Agents keep a logical identity across reconnects. Heartbeats and leases handle
            liveness; dead agents get reaped, not ignored.
          </dd>
        </div>
        <div>
          <dt>smart broker, dumb routing</dt>
          <dd>
            The broker is an LLM agent that can reason and self-heal. The routing beneath it is
            deterministic policy code.
          </dd>
        </div>
        <div>
          <dt>RALPH loop</dt>
          <dd>
            An autonomous maintenance cycle: reap dead agents, release stale claims, drain unrouted
            messages, nudge idle workers.
          </dd>
        </div>
        <div>
          <dt>workers compute, broker keeps the lights on</dt>
          <dd>
            Workers do tasks. The broker is infrastructure. They do not share a process lifetime.
          </dd>
        </div>
        <div>
          <dt>extensions stay thin</dt>
          <dd>
            Tools like <code>slack_send</code> and <code>pinet action=send</code> are shims over the
            broker. They do not own state.
          </dd>
        </div>
      </dl>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-no">§ 04<small>bootstrap</small></div>
    <div class="prose">
      <h2>Ten minutes to a working mesh</h2>
      <ol class="clauses">
        <li>
          <div>
            <span class="clause-title">Install the bridge.</span>
            <p><code>pi install npm:@pinet/slack-bridge</code></p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>
          <div>
            <span class="clause-title">Create the Slack app from the manifest.</span>
            <p>
              At <a href="https://api.slack.com/apps">api.slack.com/apps</a>, create an app "from a
              manifest" and paste <a
                href="https://github.com/gugu91/extensions/blob/main/slack-bridge/manifest.yaml"
                ><code>manifest.yaml</code></a
              >. Socket Mode, scopes, events, and slash commands are configured for you.
            </p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>
          <div>
            <span class="clause-title">Collect two tokens.</span>
            <p>
              An app-level token (<code>xapp-…</code>, with <code>connections:write</code>) and a
              bot token (<code>xoxb-…</code>) from OAuth &amp; Permissions.
            </p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>
          <div>
            <span class="clause-title">Configure pi.</span>
            <p>
              Add tokens, a runtime mode, and your Slack user ID to
              <code>~/.pi/agent/settings.json</code>:
            </p>
            <pre><code>{`{
  "slack-bridge": {
    "botToken": "xoxb-…",
    "appToken": "xapp-…",
    "runtimeMode": "single",
    "allowedUsers": ["U_YOUR_USER_ID"]
  }
}`}</code></pre>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>
          <div>
            <span class="clause-title">Start pi.</span>
            <p>Pinet appears in your Slack sidebar. DM it, mention it, or run <code>/pinet</code>.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
      </ol>
      <p>
        Full walkthrough, access control, and the complete configuration table live in the <a
          href="/slack-bridge/">Slack Bridge document</a>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-no">§ 05<small>provenance</small></div>
    <div class="prose">
      <h2>Built by the system it enables</h2>
      <p>
        Pinet was built by agents coordinating through Slack and GitHub: the same broker, the same
        inbox, the same thread ownership described on this page. During development the mesh merged
        over fifty pull requests in a single day with minimal human intervention: workers wrote the
        code, other agents reviewed it, and RALPH cleaned up after the ones that wandered off.
      </p>
      <p>
        Humans set priorities, approve merges, and hold the API tokens. The system handles
        coordination and execution. The aim is to move you up a level, from doing every step to
        steering a mesh that coordinates itself.
      </p>
      <div>
        <a class="xref" href="https://github.com/gugu91/extensions"
          ><span class="arrow">→</span> read the source</a
        >
        <a class="xref" href="/core/"><span class="arrow">→</span> pinet core, in depth</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>

<style>
  .hero {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: minmax(0, 7fr) minmax(0, 5fr);
    gap: 3rem;
    padding: 3.2rem 0 3rem;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule);
    align-items: start;
  }

  .hero h1 {
    font-family: var(--sans);
    font-size: clamp(2.1rem, 4.6vw, 3.3rem);
    line-height: 1.04;
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: -0.025em;
    margin: 0 0 1.2rem;
  }

  .dek {
    font-size: 1.08rem;
    line-height: 1.6;
    max-width: 54ch;
    margin: 0 0 1.4rem;
  }

  .dek a {
    color: var(--ink);
    text-decoration: underline;
    text-decoration-color: var(--signal);
    text-decoration-thickness: 1.5px;
    text-underline-offset: 3px;
  }

  .hero-copy .small-note {
    display: block;
    margin: -0.4rem 0 1.2rem;
  }

  .hero-figure {
    padding-top: 0.5rem;
  }

  @media (max-width: 900px) {
    .hero {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
      gap: 2.2rem;
      padding-top: 2.4rem;
    }
  }
</style>
